<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
    <title>HOARSENESS OF VOICE</title>
    <link href="Case_sheet_styles.css" id="light-styles" rel="stylesheet">
    <link href="Case_sheet_styles_dark.css" id="dark-styles" rel="alternate stylesheet"
      title="dark">
  </head>
  <body> <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode">🌙 Dark Mode</button>
    <h4>Hoarseness of Voice (Dysphonia)</h4>
    <p></p>
    <div class="ent General">
      <h3>1ST COMPLAINT: HOARSE / ROUGH / WEAK VOICE</h3>
      <!-- S: Site -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>S</strong>:
            Site / Sensation</span>
          <ul>
            <li>VOICE CHANGE ONLY:
              <ul>
                <li class="ent ortho-specific">Benign vocal cord lesions
                  (nodules, polyps)</li>
                <li class="ent cns cvs neurological">Vocal cord paralysis</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>THROAT <b>PAIN </b>/ SCRATCHINESS:
              <ul>
                <li class="infectious ent respiratory">Acute Laryngitis
                  (viral/bacterial)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>HEARTBURN </b>/ LUMP SENSATION:
              <ul>
                <li class="git cvs endocrine">Laryngopharyngeal Reflux (LPR /
                  Silent Reflux)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Does it feel like the problem is in your throat or
          voice box? Do you have any pain, scratchiness, or a feeling of a
          lump?"</span> </div>
      <!-- O: Onset -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>O</strong>:
            Onset</span>
          <ul>
            <li>SUDDEN:
              <ul>
                <li class="infectious ent respiratory">Acute Laryngitis (often
                  after a cold)</li>
                <li class="ent cvs emergency">Vocal cord hemorrhage (after
                  shouting/coughing)</li>
                <li class="ent surgery cvs">Post-intubation or neck/chest
                  surgery</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>GRADUAL / PROGRESSIVE:
              <ul>
                <li class="ent ortho-specific psychiatric">Vocal cord
                  nodules/polyps (from voice overuse)</li>
                <li class="git cvs endocrine respiratory">Chronic laryngitis
                  from reflux or smoking</li>
                <li class="oncology ent cns"><b>Red flag: Malignancy,
                    Neurological cause</b></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"When did you first notice the change in your
          voice? Did it happen overnight, or has it been developing over time?"</span>
      </div>
      <!-- D: Duration -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>D</strong>:
            Duration</span>
          <ul>
            <li>ACUTE (&lt; 3 weeks):
              <ul>
                <li class="infectious respiratory">Most commonly acute
                  laryngitis</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>CHRONIC (&gt; 3 weeks):
              <ul>
                <li class="ent oncology"><b>Red flag: Requires ENT referral for
                    laryngoscopy to rule out serious pathology</b></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"How long has your voice been hoarse?"</span> </div>
      <!-- A/R: Aggravating / Relieving Factors -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>A/R</strong>:
            Aggravating &amp; Relieving Factors</span>
          <ul>
            <li>AGGRAVATING:
              <ul>
                <li>vocal overuse</li>
                <ul>
                  <li>Prolonged speaking, shouting, singing </li>
                </ul>
                <li class="lifestyle psychiatric endocrine">Smoking, alcohol,
                  caffeine</li>
                <li class="respiratory ent environmental">Dry or dusty
                  environments</li>
                <li class="git cvs endocrine">Lying down (suggests reflux)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>RELIEVING:
              <ul>
                <li>Voice rest</li>
                <li>Staying hydrated</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Is there anything that makes your voice worse,
          like talking for a long time? Does resting your voice help?"</span> </div>
      <!-- C: Character -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>C</strong>:
            Character of Voice</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent cns cvs neurological">BREATHY / WEAK: Suggests poor
              vocal cord closure (paralysis, presbylarynx - aging voice)</li>
            <li class="ent infectious respiratory">ROUGH / RASPY: Common with
              laryngitis, nodules, polyps, or cysts</li>
            <li class="ent psychiatric">STRAINED / TENSE: Muscle Tension
              Dysphonia</li>
            <li class="ent ortho-specific endocrine">PITCH BREAKS / UNSTABLE:
              Common with vocal fatigue or nodules</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"How would you describe the sound of your voice
          now? Is it weak, breathy, rough, or strained?"</span> </div>
      <!-- R: Radiation -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>R</strong>:
            Radiation</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent oncology">Referred ear pain (otalgia) can be a <b class="oncology">
                laryngeal cancer</b>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Are you having any pain that travels from your
          throat to your ears?"</span> </div>
      <!-- A: Associated Symptoms -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>A</strong>:
            Associated Symptoms</span>
          <ul>
            <li>URTI(Cough, runny nose, sore throat):
              <ul>
                <li class="infectious respiratory">Acute Viral Laryngitis</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b><u>REFLUX </u></b>SYMPTOMS (Heartburn, throat clearing,
              cough worse at night):
              <ul>
                <li class="git cvs endocrine">Laryngopharyngeal Reflux (LPR)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>DYSPHAGIA (Difficulty swallowing) / ODYNOPHAGIA (Painful
              swallowing):
              <ul>
                <li class="oncology ent emergency"><b>malignancy or deep neck
                    infection</b></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>NEUROLOGICAL SYMPTOMS (Tremor, weakness, swallowing issues, gait
              problems):
              <ul>
                <li class="cns cvs neurological">Parkinson's, </li>
                <li class="cns cvs neurological">Stroke,</li>
                <li class="cns cvs neurological">Myasthenia Gravis</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>AUTOIMMUNE / SYSTEMIC DISEASES:
              <ul>
                <li class="rheumatic ent">Rheumatoid Arthritis (cricoarytenoid
                  joint involvement)</li>
                <li class="rheumatic ent">Sj&ouml;gren's Syndrome (dryness
                  affecting vocal cords)</li>
                <li class="rheumatic ent emergency">Granulomatosis with
                  Polyangiitis (GPA/Wegener's)</li>
                <li class="rheumatic ent">Sarcoidosis (laryngeal granulomas)</li>
                <li class="rheumatic ent">Amyloidosis (protein deposition in
                  vocal cords)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>INFECTIOUS CAUSES (Non-viral):
              <ul>
                <li class="infectious emergency">Laryngeal Tuberculosis</li>
                <li class="infectious emergency">Laryngeal Fungal Infections
                  (Aspergillosis, Mucormycosis Actinomycosis</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>FUNCTIONAL/PSYCHOGENIC VOICE DISORDERS:
              <ul>
                <li class="psychiatric ent">Conversion Disorder/Aphonia</li>
                <li class="psychiatric ent">Psychogenic Dysphonia</li>
                <li class="psychiatric ent">Functional Voice Disorder</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>OTHER ENDOCRINE/METABOLIC CAUSES:
              <ul>
                <li class="endocrine">Acromegaly (deepening of voice)</li>
                <li class="endocrine">Cushing's Syndrome</li>
                <li class="endocrine">Addison's Disease</li>
                <li class="gynaecology endocrine">Pregnancy-related voice
                  changes</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>IATROGENIC CAUSES:
              <ul>
                <li class="surgery cvs">Post-intubation Vocal Cord Paralysis</li>
                <li class="oncology ent">Radio/Chemo-related Voice Changes</li>
                <li class="surgery">Thyroid/Neck Surgery Complications</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>SYSTEMIC SYMPTOMS (Fever, night sweats, weight loss):
              <ul>
                <li class="oncology infectious"><b>Red flag for malignancy or
                    chronic infection (e.g., TB)</b></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>HYPO/HYPER/THYROID SYMPTOMS (Fatigue, weight gain, cold
              intolerance):
              <ul>
                <li class="endocrine cvs">Hypothyroidism can cause a deep,
                  gravelly voice.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Have you noticed any other symptoms like coughing,
          heartburn, difficulty swallowing, fever, or weight loss?"</span> </div>
      <!-- P: Progression -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>P</strong>:
            Progression</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="infectious respiratory">IMPROVING: Likely self-limiting
              cause like acute laryngitis.</li>
            <li class="oncology ent cvs">WORSENING: Concerning for a growing
              lesion (benign or malignant).</li>
            <li class="ent psychiatric git">FLUCTUATING: Common with vocal
              fatigue, muscle tension, or reflux.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Since it started, has your voice been getting
          better, worse, or does it fluctuate?"</span> </div>
      <!-- P: Pattern -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>P</strong>:
            Pattern</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="git cvs endocrine">WORSE IN MORNING: Classic for LPR
              (reflux overnight).</li>
            <li class="ent cns cvs neurological">WORSE AS DAY PROGRESSES: Vocal
              fatigue, Myasthenia Gravis.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Is there a time of day when your voice is
          particularly bad?"</span> </div>
      <!-- E: Effect on life -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>E</strong>:
            Effect on Life</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="occupational social psychiatric">Assess impact on
              occupation (teacher, singer, call center) and social interaction.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"How has this voice change affected your work and
          your daily life?"</span> </div>
      <!-- R: Red Flags -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>R</strong>:
            Red Flags</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="oncology ent"><b>PERSISTENCE &gt; 3 WEEKS: Any hoarseness
                lasting more than 3 weeks requires ENT referral.</b></li>
            <li class="respiratory emergency cvs"><b>AIRWAY OBSTRUCTION:</b>
              Stridor (noisy breathing) or difficulty breathing.</li>
            <li class="oncology lifestyle"><b>SUSPECTED MALIGNANCY:</b>
              Associated with smoking history, weight loss, difficulty/painful
              swallowing, coughing up blood (hemoptysis), or a neck lump.</li>
            <li class="surgery ent cvs"><b>RECENT NECK/CHEST SURGERY OR TRAUMA:</b>
              Risk of recurrent laryngeal nerve injury.</li>
            <li class="cns cvs neurological"><b>ASSOCIATED NEUROLOGICAL
                SYMPTOMS.</b></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"I need to ask a few final questions to ensure
          we're not missing anything serious."</span> </div>
      <!-- S: Scale -->
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>S</strong>:
            Severity / Scale</span> </div>
        <span class="verbal">"On a scale of 1 to 10, with 10 being the worst
          possible voice, how would you rate your hoarseness today?"</span> </div>
    </div>
    <!-- Scripts can be placed at the end -->
    <script src="theme-toggle.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
